---
import Base from "../../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="OpenAI-compatible server setup · Cloud Speech for Chrome"
  description="Connect any OpenAI-compatible text-to-speech server to the Cloud Speech Chrome extension: run your own model locally, or use a hosted service."
  root="../../"
  active="custom"
>
  <main class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-12">
    <p>
      <a class="link text-sm text-stone-600" href="../../#guides">← Back to all guides</a>
    </p>

    <header class="mt-8">
      <p
        class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full bg-custom/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-stone-700"
      >
        <span class="h-2 w-2 rounded-full bg-custom"></span>
        Setup guide
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
        Set up an OpenAI-compatible server
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
        Many speech servers speak the same API as OpenAI's <span class="value"
          >/v1/audio/speech</span
        > endpoint, and the extension can talk to any of them. You give it a server URL, and
        optionally an API key, a voice list, and a model name. There are two ways to get such a
        server; pick the one that fits you.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="mt-8 grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <a class="group card card-hover p-6" href="./local/">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <h2 class="font-semibold">Run your own model</h2>
          <span
            aria-hidden="true"
            class="ml-auto text-stone-300 transition-colors group-hover:text-ink"
          >
            →
          </span>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
          Free and private: a speech engine on your own machine, no per-character charges.
          Needs your own hardware.
        </p>
      </a>
      <a class="group card card-hover p-6" href="./hosted/">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <h2 class="font-semibold">Use a hosted service</h2>
          <span
            aria-hidden="true"
            class="ml-auto text-stone-300 transition-colors group-hover:text-ink"
          >
            →
          </span>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
          No setup beyond an account and an API key. You pay the service per use, at its own
          rates.
        </p>
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Service compatibility -->
    <section class="card mt-12 scroll-mt-24 p-6" id="services">
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2.5 text-lg font-semibold">
        <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-custom"></span>
        Where specific services stand
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-3 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-700">
        <p>
          <strong>Works directly.</strong> LocalAI, Speaches, and openedai-speech (self-hosted),
          plus hosted gateways like Groq, DeepInfra, and Lemonfox.
          <a class="link" href="https://docs.x.ai">xAI</a> serves an OpenAI-SDK-compatible API
          with a voice mode at <span class="value">https://api.x.ai/v1</span>; if your account
          has voice access, try that as the Server URL with your xAI key.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Works through a LiteLLM proxy.</strong> ElevenLabs, MiniMax, and Vertex
          AI/Gemini use their own API formats, but LiteLLM translates them to this endpoint
          shape. Point the extension at your LiteLLM proxy and configure the backend there.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <p class="mt-10 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
      Prefer a different provider? See
      <a class="link" href="../polly/">Amazon Polly</a>,
      <a class="link" href="../azure/">Azure Speech</a>,
      <a class="link" href="../google/">Google Cloud TTS</a>, or
      <a class="link" href="../openai/">OpenAI</a>.
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>
